{"id":"2106.10546","submitter":"Juan Carlos Trelles Arjona","authors":"J. C. Trelles Arjona, M. J. Mart\\'inez Gonz\\'alez and B. Ruiz Cobo","title":"Mapping the hidden magnetic field of the quiet Sun","comments":"9 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3847/2041-8213/ac0af2","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  The Sun is the only star where we can resolve the intricate magnetism that\nall convective stars harbor. Yet, more than 99% of its visible surface along\nthe solar cycle (the so-called quiet Sun) is filled with a tangled, unresolved\nmagnetism. These \"hidden\" fields are thought to store enough magnetic energy to\nplay a role in the heating of the Sun's outer atmosphere, but its field\nstrength is still not constrained. Previous investigations based on the Hanle\neffect in atomic lines claim a strong magnetization of about 100 G, while the\nsame effect in molecules show a factor of 10 weaker fields. The discrepancy\ndisappears if the magnetic field strength of the hidden is not homogeneous in\nthe solar surface. In this letter, we prove using magnetohydrodynamical\nsimulations that it is possible to infer the average field strength of the\nhidden quiet Sun magnetic fields using multi-line inversions of intensity\nprofiles in the Zeeman regime. Using this technique with 15 spectral lines in\nthe 1.5 $\\mu$m spectral range, we reveal that the spatial distribution of the\nhidden field is strongly correlated with convection motions, and that the\naverage magnetization is about 46 G. Reconciling our findings with the Hanle\nones is not obvious and will require future work on both sides, since it\nimplies an increase of the field strength with height, something that is\nphysically questionable.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 19 Jun 2021 18:22:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-14"}
